🚐Spend the day with us - Van life South Africa 🇿🇦  Today we woke up at a beautiful lakeside campsite called SwartVlei in Sedgefield 🙌 We made coffee, breakfast, cleaned the van and had a shower 🚿  Today we are off to explore some natural pools so we packed snacks and took a walk to the beachfront 🌊  Once at the beach we found a spot in the shade and setup our picnic- we tried the Harissa Hummus from Mama Alles 🥰 You just add water and stir! It was absolutely delicious guys, 10/10 😍😍 After our picnic we swam and explored the natural pools, we saw so many gosh and even a starfish ⭐️ Then it was time to head home 🚐  When we got back we filled our water tank, cleaned the dishes and cooked an early dinner 🍲  Tonight we had Moroccan Tagine from @Mama Alles  😍😍 You just add hot water to the bag or pot and in 10 minutes have a delicious meal 🙌  We ate dinner outside then had a call with family ♥️ Afterwards we drove to a spot to watch the sunset 🌅  Then it was time for snacks, netflix, brushing our teeth and heading to bed 😴  Thanks so much for watching ♥️🥰 If you are looking for super delicious convenient meals made with fresh ingredients check our @mama_alles 😍 Perfect healthy on the go meals for any occasion 🙌💗 - - - - #safyp🇿🇦 #🇿🇦 #viralsouthafrica #vanlifesouthafrica #dayinthelife #digitalnomad #travel

📍The Dead Sea. It’s incredibly cool, but it can actually be dangerous! When you swim here, remember it’s the lowest point on Earth, so the water is incredibly salty. Europe's passport-free travel zone will be welcoming Croatia.  EU countries today voted on whether or not to admit the three nations into the so-called Schengen zone - a pact between countries to abolish border checks for those travelling between their territories. Croatia received unanimous support from the 26 Schengen member states. If you were using Croatia as a base to reset your Schengen day count you might have to find a different base.  And on the other hand it means more borderless travel for those that have secured a residency or citizenship in Schengen zone.  The world is becoming a smaller place.  #freedomofmovement #borderless #moveabroad #sovereignindividual #sovereigncitizen #croatia #schengencountries #schengenvisa #digitalnomad #nomadlife

Working as a digital nomad in Antigua and Barbuda has the following benefits: •Easy internet access. With an internet speed fixed 20.95 Mbps and mobile 33.80 Mbps, you can work in any part of the world from Antigua & Barbuda, feeling at home or office. •Smooth visa application process. Applying for the Antigua & Barbuda digital nomad visa is fairly easy, and everything is done online. Moreover, you will have to wait only 14 days for an answer. •Tax exemption. As a digital nomad, you are exempt from ping income taxes in Antigua and Barbuda. •Warm climate. With a tropical savannah climate, Antigua & Barbuda has pleasing year-round weather. The best time to visit Antigua & Barbuda is November to April, when it is least rainy and hot. •Delicious cuisine. Antigua & Barbuda has become a food destination because of its fresh seafood, flavored dishes, and top-notch rum. This place is a haven for rum distilleries and sugar plantations. •Leisure activities. In Antigua & Barbuda, you can enjoy a variety of activities. Among the activities you can enjoy are exploring rainforests, swimming with stingrays, biking, kayaking, diving, snorkeling, sailing, and fishing. Working as a digital nomad in Antigua and Barbuda has the following benefits: •Easy internet access. With an internet speed fixed 20.95 Mbps and mobile 33.80 Mbps, you can work in any part of the world from Antigua & Barbuda, feeling at home or office. •Smooth visa application process. Applying for the Antigua & Barbuda digital nomad visa is fairly easy, and everything is done online. Moreover, you will have to wait only 14 days for an answer. •Tax exemption. As a digital nomad, you are exempt from ping income taxes in Antigua and Barbuda. •Warm climate. With a tropical savannah climate, Antigua & Barbuda has pleasing year-round weather. The best time to visit Antigua & Barbuda is November to April, when it is least rainy and hot. •Delicious cuisine. Antigua & Barbuda has become a food destination because of its fresh seafood, flavored dishes, and top-notch rum. This place is a haven for rum distilleries and sugar plantations. •Leisure activities. In Antigua & Barbuda, you can enjoy a variety of activities. Among the activities you can enjoy are exploring rainforests, swimming with stingrays, biking, kayaking, diving, snorkeling, sailing, and fishing. Michael and Acacia (yeti.the.van) have been living full-time in "Yeti the Van" for over a year now. They're both originally from South Africa and have spent the majority of their first year in Yeti exploring their own country and region.  In this video, Michael and Acacia want to share a little bit about their story and why they chose to live full-time in a van.  In May 2021 they started their nomadic journey living in a small Suzuki SUV. This move was done for them to begin exploring and traveling but also for them to start saving up to be able to afford Yeti.  Michael and Acacia are professional videographers and photographers and find that their nomadic lifestyle has allowed their business to expand.  This video was brought to you by Orion by Up-Switch. It is a fully integrated Nintendo Switch Portable HD 11.6 inch IPS Monitor which is perfect for gaming on the road. What it was like taking my daughter to a pediatrician in Egypt! My daughter developed a 102 degree fever during our second week in Egypt (teething). We called a doctor and they told us we could come immediately.  We arrived 15 minutes later and the doctor saw us within 10 minutes of our arrival.  It was a flat fee of $2.00 to see the doctor and he prescribed us a natural remedy to break her fever which cost $3.00 So basically,  $5.00 and 45 minutes later we were back at home taking care of the baby. two tickets to Britain’s oldest cinema please 🎟 there’s a reason why i prefer airbnbs over hotels, small local side alley restaurants to chains, living in old apartments rather than new builds or in this particular case on a visit to the cinema, going vintage rather than standard.  it’s because i love places that have stories to tell, to imagine the people that have passed through its doors, to feel its history, character and energy.  this here is considered to be the UK’s oldest cinema, first opening its doors in 1909 where it originally showed silent films with piano backing 😍.  tickets are pretty pricy at £25 each but if you’re also someone that enjoys more authentic experiences that are a little different, this cinema in London is one to watch (especially on a rainy day). 📍electric cinema, portobello, london  . . . . . #london #thisislondon #bestoflondon #itssolondon #portobello #londonuk #lifeinlondon #visitlondon #londondiaries #londonlove #nottinghill #electriccinema #vintagecinema #createyourdreamlife #createyourreality #madeformore #spiritualgrowthjourney #freedomlifestyle #slowtraveller #slowtravel #femalefounder #digitalnomadlifestyle #remotework #digitalnomadspirit #freespirit  #fulltimetraveller #solofemaletravel

when i shared the places i lived in my 20’s in a post last week, I had a lot of q’s asking how… and more importantly I noticed that there was perhaps a misconception that you need a lot of money to be able to do it, which (whilst helpful of course) definitely isn’t a must! Straight after university I left the UK for New York, with only small amount in the bank but a biggg desire to experience living everywhere i’d ever dreamed of before i’d have to ‘settle down’ in one stable job. and by either making money while abroad or finding ways to live there while spending almost nothing, i managed to moved to six countries throughout my entire 20’s. for the most part, it did mean living pretty minimally, but the experiences were anything but ✨🫶🏽 i would also like to add one thing though - if i was 20 again in this era right now, i would go straight to finding ways i can become a digital nomad to be able to travel freely long term whilst earning money online (which is what i do now too). BUT, if you just want to dip your toes into experiencing life somewhere else / make your first move solo (almost for free), then these are some great things that absolutely anyone can do, no matter who you are or how much money you have.  if you feel that pull to travel, you’ll find a way and i hope this post reaches some budding serial expats and offers some inspiration ✨ . . . . . #c#createyourdreamlifes#slowtravellerm#madetottravelf#freedomlifestylef#freedomlifel#lifejourneya#authenticexperiencel#localfindsh#hiddengemss#slowtravelf#founderstoryd#digitalnomadlifestyled#digitalnomadlife#f#freespiritf#fulltimetravellerw#womentravelsolos#solofemaletravel#m#madeformores#spiritualgrowthjourneys#selftruste#expatlifea#aupairlifea#aupairparisi#internlifei#internabroadl#lifeabroadl#liveabroads#serialexpatpersonalgrowthjourney

in my early 20’s i always had the belief that one day i would need to settle down, get a ‘real job’ and work my way up the corporate ladder as so many of us do. and this is the reason that whilst travelling, i always made sure that i did ‘something for my cv’ whether it be working at different companies, taking a language course in the country i was in, volunteering or doing extra studies along the way.  at 25 i entered my new office, to work in PR for an international agency in Berlin. and to be brief, it was three years and three promotions later, nearing burnout and feeling my soul slip away, that i got the message. “this life is not meant for you.”  and i knew it to be true. so at 28, with no financial reserve but a lot of drive to change direction, i quit my job and founded my own business (@homemade_studio 😘), then one more during lockdown (@nawaste.co) whilst also freelancing on the side.  it took a fair few years of hard work and fair few more sacrifices, but i made it back to having the freedom to experience living/working from different places around the world … and this time, purely on my terms and without an expiry date. 🦋 people ask if the decision to was scary. and i can honestly say that it wasn’t … it was the thought of staying where I was and where that path was heading that terrified me much much more ✨ i share this because your soul knows. if you feel called to have a lifestyle like this, not rooted in the traditional 9-5 path, it’s because you’re meant to. and you can 🤍 . . . . . #cre#createyourdreamlifeo#slowtravellerd#madetottravele#freedomlifestylee#freedomlifef#lifejourneyt#authenticexperiencec#localfindsd#hiddengemsc#secretspotso#slowtravelu#founderstoryg#digitalnomadlifestyleg#digitalnomadlifere#freespiritl#fulltimetravellerm#womentravelsolol#solofemaletravelad#madeformorei#spiritualgrowthjourneyl#selftrustrsonalgrowthjourney

that last weekend of October Berlin spirit.  my favourite kind of people? the free-spirits who have the courage to be no one but themselves. they don’t live bounded by expectations (societal or other), they understand that growing older doesn’t mean to stop playing, they dress how they wish, do what lights them up and they give others the feeling that they might just be able to live this way too, sooner rather than later.  and it’s one of the things i’ve always loved about Berlin. skate in your 30’s, ride a bike backwards whilst juggling, wear pink hair and a crop top as a man, take your pet cat or parrot to the park and no one will bat an eyelid… absolutely nothing is off limits here, in the name of living freely.  📍tempelhofer feld ~ an abandoned airport that’s turned into one of the best places for Berliners to picnic, skate, fly kites, play music, have  bbqs + + + . . . . . #t#thisisberlinb#berlincityb#berlinlifet#tempelhoferfelda#abandonedplacesa#abandonedplacef#freespiritf#freedomlifestylec#createyourdreamlifem#madeformores#slowtravellerm#madetottravels#slowtravelf#femalefounderd#digitalnomadlifestylee#exploregermanyf#freespiritf#fulltimetravellerw#womentravelsolos#solofemaletravelb#berlinlivingb#berlinautumnexploreberlin

People always tell me how they want to travel like me or have my life, and I have two things to say to that: 1. My life isn't all that you see on social media. There's a lot (both good and bad) that I don't post here. I have my issues, just like anyone else. But perhaps most importantly, I don't travel as much as it looks like on social media. Don't get me wrong, I travel a lot, but as an aspiring content creator I have to post travel content on a daily basis, several times a day, across multiple platforms. I can assure you I don't travel every day, or every week or every month. 2. Everyone comes from a different background and I've been very lucky when it comes to travel. I'm not going to sit here and deny my priviledge.  That said, no one handed this life to me. The content creation, solo travel and potentially being a full-time traveler, that was all me. It all started with a decision to change the way I lived and take risks in order to pursue what I wanted. And more importantly, action followed that decision. That is the most important thing. #travellife #travellifestyle #travellife✈️ #digitalnomad #digitalnomadlife #digitalnomadlifestyle #digitalnomadtravel

The digital nomad Visa is the perfect  Way to see and live in another country if you have a job that is remote or if you work for yourself. These countries will let you live there as long as you can prove that you make a certain income which most of the time is their minimum wage. Here are all the countries that I mentioned,  Norway Bahamas Portugal Germany  Barbados Greece Iceland Romania  Indonesia Italy Spain Taiwan and Mexico.  I also mentioned Australia New Zealand Ireland South Korea and Singapore do not have this program but will let you stay there for a year with a  working holiday Visa which I can talk about in another video.  As a full time traveler and digital nomad and backpacker these are some of the best tools to use to see the world for cheap, it is also a great alternative to the gap year. 📍Maligne Canyon, Jasper National Park  The deepest canyon in Jasper National Park. Measuring a depth of over 50 metres at certain points, hikers of all abilities are able to explore this amazing, all natural landscape by crossing 6 bridges which are built at various different points throughout the canyon.  With the 2nd bridge standing at the highest point of the canyon, the 3rd bridge is by far the best view you’ll get of the stunning waterfall which allows for some incredible photo opportunities. #travelbucketlist #affordabletravel #travelcouple #waterfalls #jaspernationalpark #explorealberta #travelcanada #travelblogger #digitalnomadlife #digitalnomadlifestyle #hiketok #hikealberta #hikingtips

Replying to @lisaserota  Here are all my budget travel tips and travel recommendations for someone going to visit Tokyo, Japan.  1st I would recommend  Going to all the different cities within Tokyo, Japan such as shinjuku shibuya asakusa rapungi and so on.  Then I would also recommend going to Tokyo Disneyland and sea, the studio ghibli museum, the Ramen museum, TeamLABS Tokyo and some of the more popular places like Sensoji temple, Tokyo sky tree, Tsukiji fish market, and the Imperial palace.  As for food I would recommend trying yakaniku and ramen as well as my favorite Japanese chicken Katsu curry, CoCo Ichibanya is great quick and easy for katsu curry but I may also recommend somewhere that isn't a chain that specializes in katsu curry. Additionally, I would also recommend going outside of the city to Fuji, Kyoto, Osaka and Himeji with the JR Rail pass. #tokyotravel #visittokyo #budgettraveller #budgettraveltips #fulltimetravel #fulltimetraveller #digitalnomads #japantraveltips #visitjapan #digitalnomadlifestyle

Hi, I’m Nic and I’ve been a self employed digital nomad for nearly 5 years 🤓.  I chose this lifestyle so I could travel the world and live life on my own terms 🫶🏼 Before becoming a digital nomad I had experience in Retail Store Management, HR and being an Executive Assistant. Unfortunately, my job at the time wouldn’t allow for remote working so I quit and started gigging across multiple jobs, CV Writing, Personal Assistance and Copy Typing. However, I knew I wanted to become a Content Creator as I wanted to do something more creative with my life that complimented my love for travelling so… I started documenting my life here on Instagram 🤟🏼.  After a few years, I decided to start a YouTube followed by a TikTok and next thing I know I was able to make Content Creation my full time job 🥰.  I’m a big believer in not having all your eggs in one basket when it comes to generating financial streams so I also offer coaching sessions focused on Content Creation and Van Life as well as creating and selling eBooks. When I have spare time, I make jewellery and tattoo as well 🙃 If you have any questions about being a digital nomad, ask away in the comments below 🥰 @NicRoams @NicRoams  . . #v#vanlifed#digitalnomads#selfemployeds#selfemployedlifes#selfemploymentd#digitalnomadlifed#digitalnomadsw#workforyourselfv#vanlifert#travellerf#fulltimevanliferf#fulltimetravellert#traveleverydayd#digitalnomadlifestyled#digitalnomadgirlsd#digitalnomaden#nomadlifen#nomadictnomadstories

I don’t support communism, in fact I hate it because that’s the reason why my grandmother had to escape Hungary back in 1956 with my mother in her arms through hills and wire.  However, the remains of Buzludzha are impressive not only for the shape and size but for the psychological effect it has on you as you’re approaching it and you get close to it. From the distance it looks like a spaceship that’s ready to take off and you can barely notice the bad state it is which can be only seeing once you’re next to it when you get to the top.  I will never say this is beautiful but I will say that it is on its own a good example of human legacy that hopefully never comes back again.  #bulgaria #solotraveller #digitalnomad #digitalnomadlife #digitalnomadlifestyle #easterneuropetrip

after the second week of living somewhere new, something changes and you no longer quite feel like a tourist on holiday. you’ve experienced enough things to know … which boulangeries make your favourite pain au chocolates (you know the ones with the crunchy flakes that have been baked to perfection😍), you know at which time your favourite cafes will be drenched in sun (just before it gets too busy) and can greet the waiter by name… you know what time you need to put the bin out on the street in order to be collected, what days the fresh markets are and plan your shopping  accordingly and you can navigate the maze of alleyways without relying on your google maps…  and that’s where the true appreciation comes in. for experiencing life of another set of people, in another coordinate of the world... this moment in time of a certain place, walking in the shoes of another and trying out an alternate life to see how it fits. 🇫🇷 and you … how long does it usually take you to feel ‘settled in’ in a new place?  📍aix en provence . . . . . #madeformore #createyourdreamlife #madetottravel #freedomlifestyle #freedomlife #digitalnomadlifestyle #slowtravel #slowtraveller #slowtravelling #lifejourney #authenticexperience #localfinds #localtips #freespirit #fulltimetraveller #womentravelsolo #solofemaletravel #solofemaletraveler #solofemaletraveller #provence #provencelife #aixenprovence

slow travel isn't always necessarily to do with time. it's true that we don't always have the opportunity to spend a few weeks or months in one place, but even still, we can slow down our pace.  avoid trying to squeeze everywhere and everything in, making a checklist of must do's and a plan to see them back to back, let go of spending time in the popular places that actually don't make your soul light up and release any feelings of guilt that may come with believing that you're seeing less. by doing this, you'll come away with actually experiencing more. go on long walks without a set direction, stopping at whichever place, restaurant or cafe that 'just feels good,' to you, be open to long conversations with strangers, and spend some leisurely time watching the world go by and soaking it all in. by all means, have a little pre-list of highlights you'd love to see, but stay open to the flow and the beauty that comes with going slow. 📍aix en provence . . . . . #madeformore #createyourdreamlife #madetottravel #freedomlifestyle #freedomlife #digitalnomadlifestyle #slowtravel #slowtraveller #slowtravelling #lifejourney #authenticexperience #localfinds #localtips #freespirit #fulltimetraveller #womentravelsolo #solofemaletravel #solofemaletraveler #solofemaletraveller #provence #provencelife #aixenprovence

🤯 I quit my office job 5 years ago and this is what my life looks like now 🤯 Yes, I still work, I just don’t live to work, I work to live 🙌🏼. Meaning my work, works around the life I want. A life where I feel as free as I can and in control of how I spend it 🫶🏼 When I was working my office job, I never understood how people made the leap, I’m going to admit it 😬… I thought wealth played a huge factor in it. But 5 years down the line I can promise you it doesn’t. When I started this life I was in debt, I had -£3000 in my bank. I was living in London, renting a flat in zone 2 and felt like I was grafting with no reward. The world I was living in was eating away my money, my freedom and my soul.  So I made huge changes, ones that I had no idea would work at the time and ones that scared the hell out of me.  But I can tell you right now, I’m so f**king grateful for past me… feeling very Snoop Dogg right now when he thanks himself for his hard work 😂. But we should all be proud of the choices we have made especially when it works out! The changes weren’t an overnight thing but this is how I basically did it 🧚‍♀️  1. I got a remote job in my evenings whilst working full time 2. I bought a van to become my home 3. When the van was done I quit my office job and left renting, the income from my remote job was enough to keep the wheels rolling and pay off the debt I had accumulated  4. With my spare hours, I enjoyed life and started the business I wanted to do, become a Content Creator There were a lot of hurdles along the way, it really isn’t as simple as a list but if you want it, keep your mind focused and take every challenge as a lesson 🫶🏼 I love helping you guys tread your own path so if you have any questions ask away in the comments below 👇🏽 @NicRoams @NicRoams  #dig#digitalnomadlifem#nomadlivingg#digitalcreatorst#alternativelifestylev#livingontheroadv#livinginavanl#fulltimetravellerm#nomadictn#vanlifera#travellerlifeg#digitalnomadlifestylem#nomadgirlsngirlsrule

Full time travel does not equal a vacation. It is easy to see full time travelers and digital nomads as well as people on gap years as taking just extended vacations these long elaborate trips where they are staying in nice places they are doing all of the touristy things and seeing the sites. What's important to know is that most of the time that is not the case, people that travel full time do so mostly because they are either already working still and are retaining a full time remote job or a part time remote job that funds this experience, or they are potentially working at the places they're traveling like working for the hostel or for a ski resort, or they've saved a lot of money, sometimes over the course of years to be able to afford the travel they are currently doing. Still though the truth of the matter is that when you are traveling full time unless you use credit card  Sign on bonuses and are travel hacking like I am most of the experiences that you are having are staying in hostels for extremely cheap not paying for expensive hotels like many would on vacation, they may have quit comfy jobs at home and are just living life. It is no longer a vacation it is your life, and that is why people traveling full time aren't spending as much every day because they're not as rushed to see absolutely everything in every place they have the time to take it slow, Eat at street food vendors instead of nice restaurants, take the free walking tours instead of the one's Trip Advisor recommends for a couple $100 And focus on local experiences rather than catered experiences to tourism. Full time travel is about the experiences and feeling the place in its most authentic way not about seeing everything that you can and spending all of your money.  That's my take anyway let me know what you think? T I P S 👨🏾‍💻 - A couple things I’ve learned in the first month of my nomadic journey.  1. Ditch the heavy luggage! - I found that packing light is a MUST when you plan to move around from place to place in a short period of time.  Starting in Europe, the buildings are much older and you might find yourself staying on the 3rd or 4th floor with no elevator through multiple cities. Carrying that 50lb hard side will get exhausting even when just trying to pull it along the old stone roads. Once you get comfortable you won’t wear most of what you bring anyhow so PACK LIGHT, trust me 🙏🏾 2. It might get lonely - You’re solo-traveling so of course you know you’re going to be alone, but feeling lonely is a totally different thing to prepare for.  It’s bound to happen especially if you visit smaller cities where some of the popular apps to meet people aren’t as widely used.  I found that booking a tour of the city or food tour can be a great way to meet others and help feel less alone on your trip.  Also, just getting outside and being around the locals by working at a cafe or having a drink a bar can get you out of a rut if you find yourself in one.  These are just a couple things I’ve learned so far.  I’ll continue to share more tips as I continue to travel 👨🏾‍💻 What questions do you have about the nomad life or solo-traveling ? When I first became a digital nomad in 2017, I DID pay for an entire storage unit and I regretted it almost immediately 🥸  It cost a lot of money to maintain, and after 3 months I flew back from Panama City to Chicago to clean it out. Email I send after an interview when I don’t get the job. It’s easy to take rejection personally But there are many reasons why you don’t get a job 1. Maybe the budget was cut and they lost the position 2. They could have promoted someone or demoted someone already at the company 3. Or Maybe they gave the job to someone else and that person quit after 1 week Either way, an email like this keeps your options open.  Email: Good afternoon, I want to thank you for your time on Monday. It was a pleasure getting to learn more about the company during the interview process.  Although I was disappointed to hear that I was not selected for the position, I do trust in your leadership when selecting the best fit candidate. If anything with this position changes or you feel I would be a suitable candidate for another role at your company, I would be happy to come back for additional consideration. I wish you and your team all the best in your search. #jobinterviewtips #jobinterviewquestions #jobhunt #careeradvice #jobinterviewprep #jobinterviewpreparation #careercoaching #careeradvice #careerchange #corporateamerica #rejectionfromajob #corporatelife #engineering #projectmanagement #supplychain #jobrejection #applyingtojobs #jobapplications #techjobs #remotework #worklife #workplaceboundaries #career #careertips #9-5 #corporatejob #professionalwomen #professionalmen #corporatelife #relatable #mentorship #dreamjob

Would you take a helicopter from the airport instead of a taxi?? During my last visit to New York City, I got stuck in a taxi for over two hours from the airport to Manhattan 🤯🫣 plus it was almost $200 I heard about helicopters that can do it in under FIVE minutes, for around the same price, so I thought I would try it! My first ride was $195, and $50 bucks off (I know a code for first timers) so it was the same price as Uber, but a fraction of the time.  Carry on bag is free, checked costs a hefty extra.  The lounge came with free drinks, the 5-min ride had the most breathtaking views of the city, and I was shocked at how smooth and quick everything was 😍😍 This saved me a ton of time and I would do it again in a heartbeat, especially if my flight was coming in or departing around rush-hour. * * * * #helicopter #blade #travellife #avgeek  #nycviews #helicopterride #travelhacks #traveltips #nyctips

Últimamente veo a mucha gente en redes sociales animando a otros a no meterse a estudiar una carrera para seguir su pasión de viajar por el mundo y me parece un posición muy buena si no sabes que quieres estudiar o hacer con tu vida, pero estudiar y viajar al mismo tiempo también es POSIBLE. No dejes de estudiar la carrera que te va a dar el futuro que sueñas por pensar que ambos estilos de vida no son compatibles. Estudia, trabaja dando clases, de camarero, en eventos… y viaja cada vez que puedas, aprovecha esos huecos después de exámenes y esos vuelos por menos de 30€, y sobre todo no te pongas obstáculos, si nadie quiere viajar contigo ve tu solo, encuentra gente en redes que quiere hacer lo mismo que tú (que hay mucha), sal de tu zona de comfort y conoce el mundo. #travel #study #travellife #reflexion #happiness #diving #surf #ocean #viraltiktok

[Freelancing Life] Besides doing a 9 to 5 job, I also have some freelance jobs as my additional income. Doing a freelance job while also having a full-time job mengharuskan saya untuk mengorbankan beberapa hal, seperti waktu tidur yang akhirnya lebih sedikit, waktu weekend, dan kesenangan masa muda lainnya. Beberapa minggu ini saya coba mengubah pola kerja saya, dari yang sebelummya kerja sampai larut setelah selesai full-time, menjadi kerja lebih pagi sebelum full-time. I try to sleep as early as possible setelah selesai kerjaan full-time, kemudian bangun lebih pagi untuk ngerjain side project or freelance job. Tantangan untuk terus belajar hal baru seringkali datang dari freelance job and for me this is my chance to sharpen my skills. For me, selagi masih muda, selagi energi nya masih banyak dan otak nya masih kuat untuk belajar hal-hal baru, mengorbankan kesenangan-kesenangan jangka pendek bukanlah hal yang perlu disesali.
